Eastern Cape Contralesa chairperson, Inkosi Mwelo Nonkonyana, says land in rural communities should be administered by traditional leaders on behalf of the people - not the State. JOHANNESBURG - The Eastern Cape House of Traditional Leaders is throwing its weight behind the AmaZulu King. It's opposing the scrapping of the Ingonyama Trust. WATCH: Zulu king vows to fight for land as long as he's alive Eastern Cape Contralesa chairperson, Inkosi Mwelo Nonkonyana, says land in rural communities should be administered by traditional leaders on behalf of the people - not the State. "We are the State as far as we are concerned, people are the State. Not those people who are actually elected for five years and mess up things and go. We are here for generations to come. Yes, democracy can be here for five years under our own watch. If they mess things, we must actually not vote for them," said Inkosi Nonkonyana. READ: Presidential Advisory Panel recommends review of Ingonyama Trust Act King Goodwill Zwelithini is the sole trustee, administering more than 2.8 million hectares of land in KwaZulu-Natal. The Presidential Advisory Panel on Land Reform recommended the review of the Ingonyama Trust Act. The AmaZulu King is threatening to fight all the way to the Constitutional Court. He says he is even prepared to take the matter to an International Court.